1) What are the key differences between C and Java?
-->The key differences between C and Java relate to their programming paradigm, memory management, and platform dependence.
    C is a procedural, low-level, and platform-dependent language, while Java is an object-oriented, high-level, and platform-independent language.

2) What are the key differences between C++ and Java?
-->The key differences between C++ and Java lie in their core design philosophies: C++ provides low-level control for maximum performance in system-level
    programming, while Java prioritizes portability and automatic memory management for enterprise and web applications.

3) Is Java fully object-oriented? Explain.
-->No, Java is not a fully or purely object-oriented language. While it is primarily an object-oriented programming (OOP) language that
    supports core OOP principles, it deviates from strict object-oriented purity for reasons of performance and practicality. 
